Bye-bye to accidents in new games Tsuruoka Police Department collaborates with related organizations to raise safety awareness|Yamagata Shimbun
At the bicycle class held as the start event of the operation, a collision experiment between a car and a bicycle was conducted = Tsuruoka City, Shoko Gakuen Driving School
The Tsuruoka Police Station (Chief Keizo Sato) has launched the "Bye-Bye Zero Accident Strategy" in an attempt to eliminate accidents involving bicycles and motorcycles, which have a high rate of occurrence in the area in recent years.
In addition to raising awareness of accident prevention together with traffic safety organizations in the jurisdiction, we will work to strengthen the crackdown on violations of traffic rules by bicycles.
There have been three fatal traffic accidents in the department this year, with people driving motorcycles and bicycles dying.
Although the number of accidents is decreasing, the rate of accidents involving bicycles is about 11.7% as of June 30, and the rate of accidents involving motorcycles is about 5.8%, both higher than the prefectural average.
In particular, the rate of bicycle accidents in the past five years has been higher than the prefectural average, and we planned a strategy to overcome this situation.
The name of the operation is a combination of "bike" and "bicycle" to mean accident eradication.
We will ask related organizations to provide driving guidance to the elderly and to use luminescent reflectors in traffic safety classes and other events.
The police will issue yellow cards (guidance warning sheets) in the event of a crackdown to warn people to be careful.
The opening ceremony of the operation was held on the 21st at the Shoko Gakuen Driving School in Tsuruoka City.
About 30 people attended the meeting, and Chief Sato said, "I would like to ask for your cooperation in order to reduce even one tragic accident."
The person in charge of the department presented the policy and the activities of each group.
As a starting event for the operation, a bicycle class was held.
A police officer in a car demonstrated how the impact applied to a bicycle differs when the vehicle collides with a bicycle with the brakes applied and when it collides at a speed of about 55 kilometers per hour without stepping on the brakes.
Koichi Kaneuchi, chairman of the Tsuruoka District Regional Traffic Safety Activity Promotion Committee, said, "I realized once again the horror of traffic accidents, and I would like to call attention not only to the elderly but also to young people."
