Instantly detects the occurrence of a crisis from online information, also judges hoaxes (JBpress) --Yahoo! News
"I want to know where and what kind of disasters and accidents have occurred as soon as possible!" 」
This is not limited to news organizations such as television and newspapers, but there is a strong need for it in many companies, such as social infrastructure companies and local governments.
The service that responds to this is "Specti" developed by Spectee, which analyzes information using AI.
Photos: Alerts from Specti Determine the Authenticity of Social Media Information by a Specialized Team
Nowadays, the means by which people first learn about the occurrence of disasters and accidents is beginning to shift from television to online information (social media).
Social media such as Twitter has become an important medium for disseminating information immediately after a disaster or accident occurs.
However, it is difficult to constantly monitor the overflow of information and extract useful information from it.
Specti has a function to detect information related to natural disasters and accidents from information flowing through social media such as Twitter, Instagram, and Facebook, analyze the content, determine the authenticity of the information, and distribute it to the user company.
"A wide range of events with a negative impact that halt or stagnate social activities are positioned as 'crises,'" said Kenjiro Murakami, CEO of the company, and is a crisis management support service that visualizes various crises occurring in Japan and overseas.
NHK was the first major use case of Specti at the time of the Kumamoto earthquake in April 2016, and the adoption movement has since spread rapidly among companies.
In addition to news organizations such as TV stations and newspapers, more than 350 companies in Japan, including companies that support social infrastructure such as electricity, gas, and transportation, as well as municipalities across the country, are currently using Specti.
■ Analyze posts to determine the type and location of the "crisis"
Specti distributes information in four steps: "information gathering", "analysis and content classification", "titling", and "authenticity determination".
The user company specifies in advance the area (prefecture, municipality, etc.) and the category of crisis (disaster, accident, etc.) to be collected.
Specti collects posts that fall under that designation using APIs provided by social media.
It then analyzes and categorizes the text, images, and videos in the collected posts.
For example, if you see a video of a fire truck, black smoke coming from a building, and orange flames coming out of a room, classify it as a "fire."
In addition, an image of an overturned car is classified as "traffic accident", and an image of a road covered with water is classified as "road flooded".
Specti also estimates the location of disasters and accidents.
"We often don't know the location from the posts, so we use a combination of various information to make estimates," says Murakami.
For example, if a road sign or billboard is reflected in an image or video, the place name information is extracted from it and compared with the place name database to identify the location.
