Mobile number porting, strict eyes on excessive retention.
What about fees and points?
(New Switch) --Yahoo! News
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications (MIC) is in full swing considering a review of the Number Forwarding System (MNP), which allows users to use their existing phone numbers as they are when changing mobile carriers.
At the meeting of experts on the 21st, the government announced a policy to revise the MNP guidelines established in 2004.
There are a wide range of specific issues, such as the nature of MNP fees and the pros and cons of retaining those who wish to move out.
While a backlash from telecommunications companies is expected, attention will be focused on whether it will lead to the promotion of healthy market competition.
The darkness of telecommunications companies that are far from unlimited mobile phone switching When MNP was first introduced in 06, the user burden fee was 2,000 yen, but now it is 3,000 yen.
The MNP fee income of the three major mobile telecommunications companies is estimated to be 15.9 billion yen per year.
On the 21st, the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications (MIC) listed the current situation surrounding MNP at the "Working Group (WG) on the Verification of Competition Rules," a panel of experts that discusses the competitive environment in the telecommunications market.
The time for issuing MNP reservation numbers, which are required for consumers to move to other telecommunications companies, was also cited as a key factor.
Major telecommunications companies accept applications on the web, but due to the convenience of operating their core systems, the reception hours are mainly from 9 to 20 o'clock.
In the WG document, it was clearly stated that the direction of future consideration would be an all-day response in principle.
It is also a problem that mobile carriers try to retain people who wish to move out with MNP by awarding points.
This is based on the judgment that excessive retention may impede fair competition.
Shunichi Kita, a partner at Nomura Research Institute, who is a member of the WG, said, "It is important to thoroughly implement this process first, as we will give users time to explain the provision of economic benefits or obtain permission from users, and for those who do not give permission, we will promptly issue a number and terminate it."
However, among the series of issues, there is a structural problem with MNP fees: "The higher the fee, the more difficult it is for customers to leave the company, so it is difficult to motivate them to actively lower it" (a person in charge of the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications).
If some businesses take the initiative to lower MNP fees, there is a concern that the outflow of customers from the company will increase, and the company's efforts will not be rewarded.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications has also pointed out that many countries overseas do not require user fees for MNP, and it is possible that this will be the case in Japan.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications intends to compile a report on the results of the WG around September-October, after which it will begin the process of revising the MNP Guidelines.
The timing of the revision is expected to be after 21.
Mobile carriers are likely to have a headache when it comes to sales and customer support.
